title: For Sale:  1952 SKS Russian TULA 7.62x39mm Caliber Semi-Automatic Carbine-Very Nice
location: SW Oklahoma City, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
The SKS TULA is a Russian 7.62x39mm caliber semi-automatic carbine

The SKS carbine was rather quickly phased out of first-line service, replaced by the AK-47, but remained in second-line service for decades afterwards. It is today popular on the civilian surplus market in many countries. The SKS was the first weapon chambered for the 7.62x39mm.

All military SKSs have a bayonet attached to the underside of the barrel, which is extended and retracted via a spring-loaded hinge. The SKS is easily field stripped and reassembled with no tools. The rifle has a trapdoor in the butt-stock, with a cleaning rod running under the barrel. The SKS trades accuracy for ruggedness, ease of maintenance, ease of use, and low manufacturing cost. The SKS is a simple design that is highly effective and rugged.

This 1952 SKS TULA rifle is in exceptional condition. On a scale of 1-10 with 10 being the best, I would have to rate is as an 8.85-9. Since I purchased this rifle many years ago, I have fired it a total of 10-20 times. All of the numbers on this rifle match, matching numbered parts.

Production history
Designer: Sergei Gavrilovich Simonov 
Designed: 1944 
Number built: 15,000,000 
Specifications
Weight: 3.85 kg (8.5 lb)[2] 
Length: 1,020 mm (40 in), M59/66: 1,120 mm (44 in) 
Barrel length: 520 mm (20 in), M59/66: 558.8 mm (22.00 in)
Action: Short stroke gas piston, tilting bolt, self-loading
Muzzle Velocity: 735m/s (2,411 f/s)
Effective firing range: 400 meters (440 yd)
Feed system: 10 round stripper clip internal box magazine and also reliable 20 round detachable box magazines are available as well.
Sights: Hooded post front sight, tangent notch rear sight graduated from 100 to 1,000 meters.

Differences from the "baseline" late Russian Tula Armory/Izhevsk Armory SKS:
Variations (1949–1956): Early Spike-style bayonet (1949) instead of blade-style. Spring-return firing pin was present on early models, and they did not have chrome bores (1949 – early 1951). The gas block had three changes: The first production stage gas block, used from 1949 through early 1950, was squared-off at a 90-degree angle. The second gas block production stage was instead cut at a 45-degree angle, seen on late 1950 to 1951 rifles. The third and final gas block stage, from 1952 through to 1956, was curved inward slightly toward the action.

If you have any questions please contact me, I will be happy to respond to you as fast as possible. I have about 20 more pictures available for you to look at, if you'd like to see them, let me know at I will send them to you in an e mail. If you are interested in making me a buy it now offer, I would be happy to consider your offer.

VMAC9-101 Nickle Plated 9mm pistol.  The VMAC is a descendant of the famous Military Armament Corporation machine pistol manufactured in the early 1980’s. Like the MAC 10 they are made of a formed sheet metal lower receiver containing the trigger mechanism and square tube upper receiver, housing the barrel and bolt assembly. title: For Sale:  Velocity VMAC
postcontent:
Nickle plated "Mac 10" approx. 100 rounds fired without a failure. Cleaned after every shooting. Comes with 3 32 round mags, case and owners manual. Looking for cash, will look at trades, but it would have to be something amazingly in my favor.

VMAC9-101 Nickle Plated 9mm pistol. The VMAC is a descendant of the famous Military Armament Corporation machine pistol manufactured in the early 1980’s. Like the MAC 10 they are made of a formed sheet metal lower receiver containing the trigger mechanism and square tube upper receiver, housing the barrel and bolt assembly. The barrel has a thread size of ¾ x 10 for any accessories you may want. The magazine well is incorporated in the pistol grip. It uses the blow-back unlocked bolt design. All internal parts have a manganese phosphate finished IAW 5.3.1.2 of Mil-STD-171, the U. S. governments recommended protective finish for steel. The frame has an Electroless Nickel finish which is an autocatalytic chemical reduction process that deposits a nickel-phosphorus alloy in a uniformly hard, highly protective finish. By increasing surface hardness, electroless nickel improves resistance to friction, wear and corrosion. This process prolongs the service life of parts by 2 to 10 times.

 Upper description from PSA
           Once upon a time, a "dissipator" AR was created by taking a 20" rifle-length gas system upper and cutting the barrel down to 16".  This allowed the shooter to keep the long sight radius of a rifle for accuracy, but keep the carbine length barrel for maneuverability.  The proximity of the gas port to the muzzle, however, played havoc with timing and made reliability a hit or miss proposition.   Advances in AR technology  have produced reliable carbine and mid-length gas systems, that can be hidden using low-profile gas blocks.  This allows for a front sight base to be pinned in the rifle position for the longer sight radius without the worry of the unorthodox gas port location affecting operation.   We use the term "mock" to differentiate our dissipator from a cut-down rifle length version.  Our Premium Mid-length mock dissipator uses a  Chrome Moly Vanadium steel barrel that is chrome-lined for durability.

Barrel:  16" mil-spec steel barrel, chrome lined and chambered in 5.56 NATO, with a 1/7 twist, M4 barrel extension, and a Mid-length gas system with a low-profile gas block. Barrel is made for us by FN Manufacturing here in Columbia SC.

Upper: Forged 7075-T6 A3 AR upper is made to MIL-SPECS and hard coat anodized black for durability. Featuring machined T marks, and a mil-spec finish. These uppers are made for us right here in the USA by a mil-spec manufacturer.
